joint /dʒɔɪnt/

(joints) 

1. ADJ Joint means shared by or belonging to two or more people. 联合的; 共同的 [ADJ n] 

例： She and Frank had never got around to opening a joint account. 她和弗兰克还没能抽出时间开个联名账户。 

2. jointly ADV 联合地; 共同地 [ADV with v] 

例： The Port Authority is an agency jointly run by New York and New Jersey. 该港务局是纽约和新泽西共管的机构。 

3. N-COUNT A joint is a part of your body such as your elbow or knee where two bones meet and are able to move together. 关节 

例： Her joints ache if she exercises. 她的关节一运动就疼。 

4. N-COUNT A joint is the place where two things are fastened or joined together. 连接处 

例： ...the joint between the inner and outer panels. …内外嵌板的连接处。 

5. N-COUNT You can refer to a cheap place where people go for some form of entertainment as a joint . 低档娱乐场所 [非正式] 

例： They had come to the world's most famous pick-up joint. 他们来到了世界上最有名的声色场所。 

6. N-COUNT A joint is a cigarette that contains cannabis or marijuana. 大麻烟卷 [非正式] 

例： He's smoking a joint. 他在吸大麻烟。 

7. PHRASE If something puts someone's nose out of joint , it upsets or offends them because it makes them feel less important or less valued. 使某人价值被贬低 [非正式] 

例： Barry had his nose put out of joint by Lucy's aloof sophistication. 露西的冷漠世故让巴里显得很不重要。

